Thanks for your ever-helpful explanations. I would call them holiday flats. In England, there is a similar arrangement for "leasehold" flats. But there are rarely extra facilities like a pool or a gym, unless very, very expensive and in a big city. 

In Scotland, there is no such entity; you can buy a flat in a building and you are legally obliged to jointly contribute to the costs of eg fixing the roof, maintaining gutters etc.

@Nick

It’s called misdirection. Of course the common anchors might be on a deck, but a news anchor is at a DESK. That’s what makes it fun for a Saturday. I don’t want to be condescending but if you are newish then as you get more experience you will look for this. To the point that today I said this is a Katie Hoodie Saturday puzzle, I’m sure it’s a news anchor, and put DESK without a second thought.

As for the proper nouns, this is getting exasperating, no Naticks here so what’s your beef? This is part of being a Saturday solver, having to encounter names you might not know. They are there first to expand the options of the grid, and second to challenge and expand your horizons. If you want to be a top chess player, you can’t say I want to move the pieces around but not learn all the moves and strategies from great chess games. If you want to be an NFL quarterback, you can’t say I don’t want to have to throw long passes or learn any new plays. I’m sorry, you may disagree, but I will stick to my guns, this is part of what solving a weekend NYT crossword is, and should be.

